sentences: The Four Pennies were founded in 1963, and initially consisted of Lionel Morton (vocals, rhythm guitar), Fritz Fryer (lead guitar), Mike Wilshaw (bass, keyboards, backing vocals), and Alan Buck (drums)
In their homeland, the group scored a number 47 placing with their first single, 1964's "Do You Want Me To".
They then became famous for having a number one hit in the UK Singles Chart later in 1964 with "Juliet".
"Juliet" was the only 1964 Number one by a UK group not to chart in America.

Following the UK chart-topping success of "Juliet", the Four Pennies racked up subsequent 1964 UK hits with their original "I Found Out The Hard Way" and a cover version of Lead Belly's, "Black Girl".

After their first single of 1965 did not reach the UK chart, Fryer left the Four Pennies to found a folk trio called Fritz, Mike and Mo.  (The single's b-side, "A Place Where No-One Goes", found success in Turkey later that year).
1966 saw the final UK chart entry for the Four Pennies, with a cover version of Bobby Vinton's "Trouble Is My Middle Name".

They finished 1966 – and their career – with a non-charting album (Mixed Bag), and two non-charting singles: UK songwriter Charles Bell's "Keep The Freeway Open", and Tom Springfield's "No More Sad Songs For Me".
Having left the group in 1965, Fritz Fryer formed the folk-rock trio, Fritz, Mike and Mo, in collaboration with songwriter Mike Deighan and Maureen Edwards (born c. 1931).
Having left the group in 1965, Fritz Fryer formed the folk-rock trio, Fritz, Mike and Mo, in collaboration with songwriter Mike Deighan and Maureen Edwards (born c. 1931).
After the failure of Fritz, Mike and Mo, Fryer returned to the Four Pennies in 1966.
British Big Beat (1965) had the group miming to their no. 1 hit, "Juliet", whilst Pop Gear (also 1965) contained performances of both "Juliet" and "Black Girl".
Lionel Morton – vocalist / rhythm guitarist – born Lionel Walmsley, 14 August 1940, Blackburn, Lancashire, England
Fritz Fryer – lead guitarist – born David Roderick Carney Fryer, 6 December 1944, Oldham, Lancashire –  died 2 September 2007, Lisbon, Portugal, from pancreatic cancer.

Alan Buck – drummer – born 7 April 1943, Brierfield, Burnley, Lancashire – died 15 March 1994, Ealing, West London from a heart attack.

Ray Monk also deputised on rare occasions, before managing the Preston Sony Music Centre in 1987-94.
Morton, who was at one time married to the actress, Julia Foster, went on to become a children's TV presenter in the 1960s and 70s.
The Four Pennies were an English beat group most notable for their 1964 UK chart-topping song "Juliet".

After their first single of 1965 did not reach the UK chart, Fryer left the Four Pennies to found a folk trio called Fritz, Mike and Mo.  (The single's b-side, "A Place Where No-One Goes", found success in Turkey later that year).

They finished 1966 – and their career – with a non-charting album (Mixed Bag), and two non-charting singles: UK songwriter Charles Bell's "Keep The Freeway Open", and Tom Springfield's "No More Sad Songs For Me".
By the end of the year, the group had dissolved.
Having left the group in 1965, Fritz Fryer formed the folk-rock trio, Fritz, Mike and Mo, in collaboration with songwriter Mike Deighan and Maureen Edwards (born c. 1931).

Fritz, Mike and Mo recorded two unsuccessful singles for Philips, "Somebody Stole the Sun" c/w "Let Me Hear Your Voice" and "What Colour Is A Man" (a cover version of a US release by Bobby Vinton, who also provided the Pennies' "Trouble Is My Middle Name") c/w
So Now You're Gone".
After the failure of Fritz, Mike and Mo, Fryer returned to the Four Pennies in 1966.
